Finally starting to feel like the 𝙢𝙚 I deserve to feel like☀️

And by that, I simply mean feel like I'm putting myself first and finallllly seeing/feeling the benefits of it🙌

And while I know recovery isn't linear, I'm just grateful to feel like I'm going forward towards my goals instead of backward.

And my days won't stay all happy and cheery forever, but for right now.. I'm embracing the hell out of it!🤙

If you've been on the struggle bus like I have for the past several months, just know you're not alone. And if you're ever looking to talk to a mentally ill girl online who's trying to get her shit together🙃....
or if you just need a friend, my dms are always open😆🫂

Just know that there will be brighter days ahead.. even if that might feel out of reach right now. It is possible.

We got thisssss🧡
Happy Sunday.

I go outside sometimes.

And here are some pictures of my sometimes outdoor adventures because I felt like my feed needed it, just like my soul doezsssssszzzsssss.

#natureismyhappyplace 
#natureheals

I sat outside in my back yard today and caught myself thinking, "I'm so glad no one can see me right now."
Reason: I didn't like the way my body looked.

And with summer approaching, I do my best not to think negatively about my size, my weight, my skintone...but lets face it..the thoughts are there.

I've always been my worst critic.

Since I can remember, I've thought about the way I looked to others, but as I get older , I realize I've never taken into consideration how I look and feel to ME.

I might not fit into the clothes or weigh the same as I did last summer...
BUT I'M LEARNING TO BE OK WITH THAT AND THAT FEELS GOOD.

My relationship with my body is a work in progress.

I'm thankful for all my body does no matter what size, weight, shape, or shade I am.

And I hope that if you're struggling with that too, that you know you're not alone.

Diet Culture sucks.
Societal standards of beauty sucks.
The internet, in general sucks.

You're beautiful and summer ready already, bby. Give yourself the grace and love your body deserves! 🧡🌞

#allbodiesaresummerbodies

You have been criticizing yourself for years, and it hasn’t worked. Try approving of yourself and see what happens.
 — Louise Hay

In the midst of the most hectic month I've had in a long time, I sat on the floor to do my hair, looked at my myself in the mirror and thought, "I like the way my body looks." No fancy get up. No fancy lighting. No poses. Just being.

I'm getting those moments more and more frequently, and it's a feeling I'm here for🤙

It's not an overnight 'ah ha' revalation. Years of disordered eating and body image doesn't heal itself without self-care and self-love...so I guess I'm a bit proud of myself for this.🤘

Even in the choas and the bummy times, there can be a flicker of good..and we just gotta remember to look for those moments more🧡

#healingisnotlinear
#dirtyassmirror 🤪

I haven't been sharing much on here lately..

May was one of the worst months I've had in a very long time.

My dog Quilo was having major issues, and sadly, we had to put him down💔

I barely worked due to physical and emotional shit.

My car had to have a major repair.

I went to the emergency room (all is good).

I drank *almost* every. single. day and subsequently have been dealing with emotional binge eating as well (all is not good🫠).

So, easily put...I'm exhausted.
Physically, mentally, and emotionally exhausted.

I'm not ok with being down this long, and I don't plan to stay here.

Just gotta look towards bettering myself and the situations around me that trigger me.

Today, I'm hopeful. 

I'm thankful for all the good that has happened, that is happening and will continue to happen despite the setbacks and loss.

Recovery is possible.
Just gotta remind myself that I'm worth it.

I think it's finally time I talk about how I've been doing when it comes to my drinking🫠

I haven't talked much about my relationship with alcohol recently.. or talked about much of anything on here at all, actually 🙃 and of course, I have reasons for that, but I figured it was time I write about what I've been doing lately to achieve sobriety.

Welp, I started a completely different and new approach to healing my AUD (Alcohol Use Disorder) with the help of my doctor,  therapist, and a community of people taking the same steps as me. No AA, no outpatient program, no Disulfiram🤢...a new way to taking my power back from alcohol once and for all.

It's been a little over 8 weeks with this new method, and it's been the ONLY time in the last 5 years that I've not felt completely helpless around my drinking. 

I didnt realize just how much I was hurting and hindering myself with my self-sabataging due to my guilt and shame because I had drank...and this is the first approach that I've taken that completely takes the power away from those crippling feelings.

I finally feel like I've taken my motherfucking power back.

Have I found the cure to end all my problems surrounding alcohol?..Time will tell. But I'm healing and healing PRODUCTIVELY. 

I am always thankful for the sober/sober curious/alcohol free community I have through here. I might not be engaged with posts, but I see you all out here SHINING. Seeing others being open about their relationships with alcohol is a constant reminder that I'm not alone and that there IS a way to loving life without booze.
And no matter what path you're taking to get your power back from alcohol, I'm here for it and here for you.

Thanks for being here with me, friends.
Love you all.

What I don't know won't make me spiral 🫠😵‍💫🤗

I'm turning 31 in two days, and that's got me thinking about my 30th year on this planet...

Overall, I think I've had a damn good year.

I've taken a step back from posting, and that's helped me from letting this platform dictate my emotions and actions🤳

I've started therapy again🗣

I've gained weight, and with that, I've been really leaning into body acceptance and self-love🫶

I've realized that rest isn't laziness, it's necessary🛌

I've been consistent with a new medication that helps with my Alcohol Use Disorder. And i will say it's been the best thing to happen to me (in terms of recovery) in a longgggg time🧠💊

I've been lucky enough to travel to places I've never been before🇮🇪🛫🇲🇽

I've saved my money and invested in my future💰

My relationship with my partner is getting stronger by the day👩‍❤️‍👨

AND THAT MAKES MY HEART FULL.

Thanks to those of you who have reached out and been supportive through it all. Even with taking a step back from IG, i feel like this little part of the internet still always has a way of making me see the good in people.

Love you all.

🧡

I've been taking medication to help with my alcohol use for about 6 months now, and it's honestly changed my life in so many ways.

It's been such a blessing to finally find something that actually helps curb my cravings and my consumption rate..

But right now, I'm in this awkward/exhausting phase of it.

I'm honestly just drinking to drink. Even when I take my medicine, it's not seeming to hit the same way it used to.

I mean..I know it's working because without it, I'd be a damn drunken mess more days than not, but I'm just not where I wish I was with the progress.

I read about other people taking this same medication, and at this point, they've quit having cravings and have stopped drinking completely.

I know I shouldn't compare my recovery journey to others...but I'm just realizing that there's more I could be doing for myself in order to get me there.
• Setting more boundaries with people and places I go.
• Actively doing things I enjoy that have 0% to do with booze.
• Reach out to someone when my cravings hit and talk about it.
And I'm not doing much of that shit.

So, I'm here writing these jumbled feelings out. Maybe this is one of those steps I need to take to get where I want to be in this journey. I need to talk about it and not hold in all these self-doubting feelings.

I AM doing something.
I'm making these strides for myself, even if it's taking a little more time than I thought.
I just got to trust the process.

🧡

Just want to remind all of you who are struggling that you're not alone and you can do hard things.

One fucking day at a time✊️

I wouldn't call 2023 my grandest year, but I don't take a single one of those days for granted🧡

I haven't drank alcohol in almost 2 weeks (which is great for me), and here's some things I've noticed:

• I'm insanely more productive.
• I'm getting more restful sleep (besides waking for my new puppy🙃).
• I'm saving money..like a lot.
• I'm having way less anxiety.
• I'm feeling 'lighter' (mentally, physically, and emotionally).

And I'm also noticing:

• I fucking love it.

It's been a while since I've actually seen any benefits of not drinking, and I've forgotten how good it feels to give my body the break it deserves.

So, I'm gonna keep going. Dry January motivation definitely helps, but beyond that, I'm wanting to remember this feeling.

If anyone else is on/has been on this alcohol-free journey, what are some of the first things you noticed that improved in your life since drinking?👇💬
